          "title": "Implementing BIP for restoring fidelity bonds from seed phrases",
          "body": "Hello\r\n\r\nI recently [opened a PR](https://github.com/bitcoin/bips/pull/1341) to get a BIP number assigned for the standard for storing fidelity bonds in bip39 seed phrases. It can also be read on the gist: https://gist.github.com/chris-belcher/7257763cedcc014de2cd4239857cd36e\r\n\r\nThe fidelity bonds in joinmarket are held in bip39 seed phrases. It would be pretty nice if people could restore their fidelity bond coins by importing the same bip39 seed into another wallet, like Electrum. Also it would allow for fidelity bonds to be held in cold storage, allowing the sybil resistance of such systems to increase without hot wallet risk.\r\n\r\nI was thinking write code and open a PR to add this to Electrum along with the other BIP39 wallet types. I'm wondering if anyone has thoughts around the codebase for the best way to do that. I've read a little bit around the codebase already but not much.\r\n\r\nA big difference with the fidelity bonds BIP compared to others like bip44/bip82 is there are not an infinite number of addresses. There are only 960 time-locked addresses, one for each month from 2020-01-01 until 2099-12-01. There are no gap limits, instead the wallet always generates all 960 addresses and sync's them.\r\n\r\nTo actually spend the coin the same witness is required as any other address type: `<signature> <pubkey>`. However the `nLockTime` of the transaction has to be set to greater than the address timelock.\r\n\r\nI'm reading a bit around the Electrum code, for example here: https://github.com/spesmilo/electrum/blob/9e0a0af81a7dab4fe22aeb007fb5560f48dc6433/electrum/bip39_recovery.py I think the best way is to modify the function `bitcoin.pubkey_to_address` to take an optional parameter `index` which inside the script type can be converted to a timelock value [using the formula from the bip](https://gist.github.com/chris-belcher/7257763cedcc014de2cd4239857cd36e#timelock-derivation). Or maybe this can be done in a special if-statement instead of somehow in the `pubkey_to_address` function. Then set the gap limit to be 960. Also somewhere in the GUI should be displayed the timelock as a formatted datetime, perhaps the best way is to set the description field to be automatically set to say `2020-01-01` or whatever the date is.\r\n\r\nIf you have any thoughts for coding this up do let me know. I hope to write the code eventually. Also if you think this is all a really bad idea let me know so I don't waste time coding it up. Though hopefully I can convince you that fidelity bonds are really great, joinmarket already has hundreds of bitcoins locked up some for years, and this provides excellent protection from sybil attacks. Here's a thread explaining a bit: https://twitter.com/chris_belcher_/status/1432696845017436166 (Although the thread is several months old, the numbers are bigger now)",
